  abstract = {Saccharomyces boulardii is a probiotic yeast that has been used for promoting gut health as well as preventing diarrheal diseases. This yeast not only exhibits beneficial phenotypes for gut health but also can stay longer in the gut as compared to Saccharomyces cerevisiae. Therefore, S. boulardii is an attractive host of metabolic engineering to produce biomolecules of interest in the gut. However, the lack of auxotrophic strains with defined genetic backgrounds has hampered the use of the strain for metabolic engineering. Here, we report the development of well-defined auxotrophic mutants (leu2, ura3, his3, trp1) through CRISPR-Cas9-based genome editing. The resulting auxotrophic mutants can be used as a host for introducing various genetic perturbations, such as overexpression or deletion of a target gene using existing genetic tools of S. cerevisiae. We demonstrated overexpression of a heterologous gene (LacZ), correct localization of a target protein (red fluorescent protein) into the mitochondria using a protein localization signal, and introduction of a heterologous metabolic pathway (xylose-assimilating pathway) into the genome of S. boulardii. We further demonstrated that human lysozyme, which is beneficial for human gut health, could be secreted by S. boulardii. Our results suggest that more sophisticated genetic perturbations to improve S. boulardii can be performed without using a drug resistance marker, which is a prerequisite for in vivo applications of engineered S. boulardii.},
